e, England":"Derbyshire, England","Little Cubley, Derbyshire, England":"Little Cubley, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Trussell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Hertfordshire, Leicestershire and Essex):","nickname from Middle English <i>trus(s)el(le)</i> ‘bundle, parcel’ (Old French <i>troussel</i>), perhaps for a porter (see   Truss  ), or from the same word in the sense ‘stamp, mould (for stamping coins)’, for someone who minted coins.","variant of <b>Thrussell</b>, a nickname from Middle English <i>thros(t)el</i>, <i>thrus(t)el</i> ‘song thrush’ (Old English <i>thros(t)le</i>). Compare   Thrush  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Truss","meanings":["English (mainly Essex and Middlesex): metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>trusse</i> ‘bundle, package’ (Old French <i>trousse</i>), perhaps for a porter. See also   Trussell  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian <b>Trus</b>: nickname from <i>trus</i> ‘rabbit’, typically applied to someone thought to be a coward."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":10,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":23,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":32,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret De Trussell was born in 1305, in Little Cubley, Derbyshire, England, her father, Richard Trussell, was 55 and her mother, Roesia Pantulf, was 78. She had at least 1 daughter. She died in 1366, in Derbyshire, England, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1305–1366":"1305–1366","1377–1391":"1377–1391","1250–1275":"1250–1275","1228–1294":"1228–1294","1275":"1275","1294":"1294","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1391":"1391","1305":"1305","1228":"1228","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1366":"1366","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Little Cubley, Derbyshire, England":"Little Cubley, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1305–1366":"1305–1366","1377–1391":"1377–1391","1250–1275":"1250–1275","1228–1294":"1228–1294","1275":"1275","1294":"1294","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1391":"1391","1305":"1305","1228":"1228